records.addlTxt:
Defendant Kenneth P Shank in court with attorney Thomas K. Hackbart.  Francesco Mineo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Deputy court clerk ccp.
Case set for sentencing hearing. PSI reviewed by the parties. State placed negotiations on the record. Court finds the State has complied with the victim rights legislation. Statements made as to sentencing. Packet of photos submitted by the State received and filed. 

As to COUNT 1-
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 3 YEARS, consecutive to COUNT 3; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.  

As to COUNT 3-
Court ordered defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Correction consecutive COUNT 1. Defendant to report to the House of Correction on 9/4/15 by 10:00 a.m. Defendant may have release to care for his elderly mother for no more than 8 hours per day, five days per week, Monday through Friday. Defendant may not have release for elderly care on Saturday and Sunday. Court recommends the defendant participate in the Day Reporting Center. Defendant may have release for employment. Defendant may participate in vocational programming while at the House of Correction. 

Court STAYED the sentence on COUNT 1 and placed defendant on probation for 4 YEARS with the following conditions:
1) AODA assessment and comply with any treatment/counseling deemed appropriate;
2) Continue attending support groups at least once per month. Provide proof of attendance to agent;
3) Maintain employment of at least 30 hours per week. Participate in vocational training;
4) Provide DNA sample and pay DNA surcharge on COUNT 1. Court WAIVED DNA surcharge on COUNT 3 as it is part of a continuous course of conduct;
5) Pay all costs, fees and surcharges on COUNT 3. Court WAIVED costs, fees and surcharges on COUNT 1 as it is part of a continuous court of conduct;
6) Pay $300.00 fine as to COUNT 3;
7) Restitution set at ZERO;

Pay all costs, fees, surcharges, and fines during period of probation. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment;

Court ordered the defendant's drivers license be suspended for a period of 2 years. Defendant may apply for occupational license when eligible.

Court ordered bail on deposit to be applied towards costs, fees, fines and surcharges.

If revoked, court costs, fees, fines and surcharges be paid through collection by the department of Corrections from 25% of funds and earnings.

If revoked, defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program. The defendant is NOT eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.

Appellate rights notice given to the defendant. 
Filed;
Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence;
Sentencing Referral Form;
Driver Assessment and Driver Safety Plan;
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief;
signed Ineligible Voting Notice & Acknowledgement.
